# Candidate profile — example for skills_fit scoring.
#
# Copy this file to candidate_profile.yml and replace the placeholder
# fields (`<...>`) and example content with your own details.
#
# `profile_version` is recorded in every scored record's metadata (plus
# a sha256 of the file) so runs are comparable across profile changes.
# Bump on every meaningful edit.
#
# **Specificity wins.** The prompt explicitly rewards specific items
# ("Python data pipelines" beats "Python"). When in doubt, name the
# concrete tool, methodology, or operational scale rather than the
# category. The example values below model that — keep the same level
# of concreteness when filling in your own profile.

profile_version: "example-v1"

summary: |
  Senior systems engineer specializing in modernizing legacy production
  codebases. Strongest current evidence: a multi-year contract on a
  production network-management system handling thousands of access
  points and hundreds of thousands of unique client devices — authored
  the majority of a large C++ tree, built out the GTest/GMock test
  harness from scratch, shipped Docker/RPM build infrastructure, and
  re-architected the device data store from opaque binary blobs to
  schema-validated JSON in an embedded KV store. Comfortable end-to-
  end: design, testability refactoring, schema migration, packaging,
  deployment.

  Secondary capability in applied ML and computer vision from over a
  decade in a scientific research lab — established MLOps practice
  (PyTorch image-segmentation models trained on cloud compute,
  inference operationalized into the lab's standard analysis
  workflow), operated multi-TB on-prem data pipelines for imaging
  instruments, designed and built custom hardware/software
  instrumentation when commercial tools couldn't capture the required
  measurements.

  Currently building toward LLM application and agent-evaluation
  tooling — structured-output agents with Pydantic, local LLM
  inference, eval harnesses with ordinal metrics on hand-scored gold
  sets, data pipelines with pandas / PyArrow / Parquet.

  Years of technical mentorship from a senior research role: mentored
  graduate and postdoctoral researchers on instrumentation,
  experimental design, reproducible data analysis, and custom
  instrument build-out. Co-author on peer-reviewed papers in
  <research field>. M.S. in <engineering field> (deep-learning focus,
  conferred recently).

  Looking for fully-remote US roles, or on-site/hybrid in
  <Primary Metro Area>.

level: |
  Mid-level through principal IC. Open to tech-lead and engineering
  management roles where the technical work is substantial. Not
  seeking junior/entry-level roles given extensive professional
  experience. No professional people-management experience yet — open
  to growing into it as part of moving into enterprise. Director / VP
  / C-suite roles are out.

education:
  - "M.S., <Engineering Field> — <University Name> (conferred recently). Focus: <specialty area> with deep-learning applications (e.g., image segmentation, computer vision)."

core_skills:
  - Modern C++ (C++17 / C++20)
  - Python
  - Legacy C++ modernization (refactoring untestable code into DI-based, mockable seams)
  - GTest / GMock — test engineering and testability refactoring
  - CMake build engineering (multi-target, RPM/CPack, custom test labels)
  - SNMP / network management systems (Net-SNMP, vendor REST APIs, DHCP/DNS/RADIUS)
  - Linux development and deployment (Ubuntu local, RHEL/AlmaLinux production, GDB/Valgrind, systemd)
  - Multi-TB on-prem data pipelines for image and spectroscopy data
  - "Schema design and migration (e.g., binary blobs to schema-validated JSON in embedded KV stores, with dump/import round-tripping for analyst workflows)"
  - Systems integration around messy external dependencies

adjacent_skills:
  - Applied DL for scientific imaging (PyTorch, U-Net, OpenCV, Albumentations) with established MLOps practice — trained models on cloud compute, operationalized inference into a standard analysis workflow
  - Technical mentorship of graduate and postdoctoral researchers; university-level course taught (data processing and analysis)
  - Custom scientific instrumentation design and build (microcontrollers, single-board computers, Python)
  - Pydantic v2 schema validation as an input boundary (field/model validators, frozen models, extra=forbid)
  - pandas / PyArrow / Parquet data pipelines
  - DuckDB for SQL-on-DataFrame exploration and Parquet benchmarking
  - Hardware-in-the-loop testing and instrument control (ctypes, Flask, dataclass configs)
  - LLM evaluation tooling (ordinal metrics, gold sets, mismatch analysis)
  - Local LLM inference (Ollama, GGUF, constrained / structured outputs)
  - Cloud compute for ML training jobs with blob storage; extending toward cloud-native IaC
  - Linux systems administration and self-hosted infrastructure (Proxmox cluster, live storage migrations, observability, backups, recovery)
  - Docker / Docker Compose / containerized dev environments
  - GitHub Actions CI for Python projects (ruff + pytest pipelines)
  - Modern Python packaging (uv, pyproject.toml, src/ layout, pre-commit hooks)
  - Shell scripting and developer-environment automation
  - RPM packaging and RHEL/AlmaLinux deployment
  - Dependency injection and testable software design

preferred_domains:
  - Developer tooling and infrastructure
  - Network management / network automation
  - Legacy modernization and refactoring engagements
  - Scientific instrumentation and engineering software
  - Hardware/software integration
  - Test engineering / validation systems
  - LLM applications and agent evaluation tooling
  - Data pipelines for operational systems
  - Automation
  - Consulting / professional-services engineering (long-running technical contracts)
  - Research-engineering / applied science (publishable, reproducibility-focused work)

avoided_domains:
  - Ad-tech
  - High-frequency trading
  - Pure web/CRUD frontend work / SaaS forms-over-data
  - Hype-driven "AI" products with little engineering substance
  - Growth-hacking / engagement-optimization products

constraints:
  - "Location: prefer fully-remote (US-based) or on-site/hybrid in <Primary Metro Area>. Upstream filters enforce this — flag any clear violations as hard_concerns (e.g., on-site requirement elsewhere that slipped through), but do not reduce fit_score on location alone."
  - "Based in <Time Zone> — flag tz-restricted 'remote' postings from incompatible regions as hard concerns"
  - No required relocation
  - No frequent travel (>15 days/year)
  - Prefer full-time roles; open to contract or contract-to-hire when fit is strong
  - "Compensation: $<target>K target, $<stretch>K+ stretch, $<floor>K floor. Postings substantially below floor (under ~$<reject>K total comp, ~20%+ below) MUST be flagged in hard_concerns as 'compensation substantially below candidate floor' — dispatcher rejects these regardless of fit. Postings between $<reject>K and $<floor>K: flag in hard_concerns but score on other criteria."

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Items below are not currently consumed by the prompt (utils.py reads only
# the 8 fields above — summary, level, education, core_skills,
# adjacent_skills, preferred_domains, avoided_domains, constraints). Kept
# here for the Phase G profile-audit session to decide what to expose. They
# do NOT increase fit scores in this first pass.
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Things you have light exposure to or are developing toward — NOT evidence
# of shipped skill. The Phase G prompt should be told these are growth-
# direction context, not credit toward a fit score.
aspirational_or_growth:
  - Agentic / multi-agent orchestration (LangGraph, critic patterns)
  - Vector databases / production RAG systems
  - Kubernetes at depth
  - MLOps orchestrators (Airflow, Prefect, Dagster)
  - Cloud-managed data warehouses (Databricks, Snowflake, BigQuery)
  - OpenTelemetry / LLMOps observability
  - People management of direct reports
  - Cloud-native IaC (Bicep, Terraform)

# Evidence highlights — credibility signals that don't fit cleanly into
# skill lists but matter for senior+/staff/principal/leadership roles. Not
# consumed by the v1 prompt; reserved for Phase G profile-audit.
evidence_highlights:
  publications:
    - "<First Author> et al. (YYYY). <Journal Name> <Volume>(<Issue>), <pages>."
    - "<First Author> et al. (YYYY). <Journal Name> <Volume>(<Issue>), <pages>."
  operational_scale:
    - "Production network: thousands of access points, hundreds of thousands of unique client devices, fast-ingestion cycle load-bearing for downstream config builds"
    - "Multi-TB on-prem data pipelines for imaging and spectroscopy data, long-term operational longevity"
  career_consistency:
    - "<Institution> Scientific Lead: <duration> — progressed from instrumentation support to lead engineer for the lab's high-throughput data infrastructure"
    - "<Consulting Company>: <duration> consulting — production data-ingestion platform on multi-year contract with <client>"
